  "text": "In the retrospective Rades experience, 36% of 124 improved ambulation (by at least one category on the Tomita scale; proportion recovering ambulation not reported) and was stable in another 50% [CITATION_1] . In this series, the median OS was 7 months. On multivariate analysis, the following factors were independently predictive of better survival: Eastern Cooperative Oncology Group performance status (3-4 vs. 1-2), ambulatory status before re-RT (ambulatory vs. nonambulatory), time to development of motor deficits (>14 vs. 8-14 vs. >8 days) and visceral metastases (no vs. yes).",
